{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489468"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:17:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"666"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/666"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.42,0.07,0.32,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111453"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93543"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45347"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111453"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman in a distressed state is brought by her room mates to the Emergency Department. The patient is unable to give a coherent history, and her friends say she has a history of diabetes and mental problems and over the last few hours appears to have taken quite a few tablets of paracetamol and drunk several jugs of water. When she started vomiting, they decided to bring her to hospital. They brought her known medications which included insulin and lithium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is drowsy with a GCS of 6, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.0C. Nothing else abnormal is found on physical examination. Her serum biochemistry is normal apart from a sodium of 109 mmol/L (135 - 145).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following initial treatments would be most appropriate for managing this patient\u0027s electrolyte abnormality?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Isotonic saline 150mL over 20 minutes","Hypertonic saline 100mL over 10 minutes","Isotonic saline 500 ml over 6 hours","Hypertonic saline 500mL over 6 hours","Fluid restriction over the next 24 hours to 500 ml"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has severe symptomatic hyponatraemia with neurological symptoms (GCS 6) and hypovolaemia, requiring prompt treatment. When serum sodium is less than 120 mmol/L with severe neurological symptoms, there is a serious risk of cerebral oedema and brain stem herniation. The priority is to raise sodium quickly; simultaneously, the rate of correction should not exceed 8-10 mmol/L in the first 24 hours. Rapid correction can cause osmotic demyelination syndrome which may lead to permanent neurological damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertonic saline 100mL over 10 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial treatment. This small, controlled bolus of 3% hypertonic saline will rapidly increase serum sodium by approximately 2-3 mmol/L, which can improve neurological symptoms while minimising the risk of overcorrection. Additional boluses may be required if symptoms do not improve, with frequent monitoring of serum sodium levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic saline 150mL over 20 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for treating severe symptomatic hyponatraemia. The sodium concentration of normal saline is insufficient to create the osmotic gradient needed to rapidly shift water out of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsotonic saline 500 ml over 6 hours\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for two reasons: it is too slow for a patient with severe neurological symptoms, and normal saline alone is ineffective for rapidly correcting severe hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertonic saline 500mL over 6 hours\u003C/strong\u003E provides too large a volume of hypertonic solution without appropriate titration and monitoring. This approach could lead to osmotic demyelination syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in this patient, who has clinical signs of hypovolaemia (BP 90/60 mmHg, pulse 100/min). Fluid restriction alone would be insufficient to address the immediate neurological emergency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe symptomatic hyponatraemia must be corrected rapidly; however, care must be taken to avoid over-correction and osmotic demyelination.","Hypertonic saline in small, controlled boluses is the treatment of choice for severe symptomatic hyponatraemia with neurological symptoms.","Serum sodium should not increase more than 8-10 mmol/L in 24 hours to prevent osmotic demyelination syndrome."],"references":["Rada AG. Two doctors sentenced in Canary Islands for failing to treat woman with hyponatraemia. BMJ 2015; 351:h4016","Hoorn EJ, Zietse R. Diagnosis and Treatment of Hyponatremia: Compilation of the Guidelines. J Am Soc Nephrol. 2017 May;28(5):1340-1349. doi: 10.1681/ASN.2016101139. Epub 2017 Feb 7. PMID: 28174217; PMCID: PMC5407738."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93543"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"666"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93543"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-14T10:29:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-14T10:30:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"666"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111453"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4961"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"